<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1046,1215]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Although the species is widespread throughout northern 
<collectingCountry box="[783,888,1046,1070]" name="Australia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Australia</collectingCountry>
, within freshwaters of the Kimberley it is known only from 
<specimenCount box="[268,433,1082,1106]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
captured at the base of King Cascades (brackish) in the Prince Regent River (
<bibRefCitation author="Allen, G. R." box="[1300,1428,1082,1106]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="89 - 96" refId="ref17973" refString="Allen, G. R. (1975) A preliminary checklist of the freshwater fishes of the Prince Regent River Reserve north-west Kimberley, Western Australia. In: Miles, J. M. &amp; Burbidge, A. A. (Eds), A biological survey of the Prince Regent River Reserve Northwest Kimberley, Western Australia in August, 1974. Wildlife Research Bulletin of Western Australia, 3, 89 - 96." type="journal article" year="1975">Allen 1975</bibRefCitation>
) and from 
<specimenCount box="[267,423,1118,1142]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
captured in the lower Ord River (
<bibRefCitation author="Storey, A. W." box="[825,967,1118,1142]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref19815" refString="Storey, A. W. (2003) Lower Ord River fish habitat survey. University of Western Australia report to Water and Rivers Commission. www. dsd. wa. gov. au / documents / Storey _ 2003 _ - _ Lower _ Ord _ River _ fish _ habitat _ survey. pdf" type="book" year="2003">Storey 2003</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[994,1080,1118,1142]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1153,1176]" captionTargetBox="[263,1325,199,1125]" captionTargetId="figure-24@33.[253,1333,193,1133]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 13. Distribution of Arrhamphus sclerolepis in the Kimberley." pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). The species inhabits shallow coastal waters, estuaries and the lower reaches of rivers (
<bibRefCitation author="Allen, G. R. &amp; Midgley, S. H. &amp; Allen, M." box="[792,988,1154,1179]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref18331" refString="Allen, G. R., Midgley, S. H. &amp; Allen, M. (2002) Field guide to the freshwater fishes of Australia. Western Australia Museum, Perth, 394 pp." type="book" year="2002">
Allen 
<emphasis box="[863,913,1155,1179]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
); thus its absence from most Kimberley rivers may be due to exclusion by waterfall barriers.
</paragraph>
